chmod <perm> <filename>  => to change file permissions
u , g , o 
+ , - 
r , w, x 
Example chmod u+rx,g+w,o-rwx file.txt
x  => 2^0 =1
w  => 2^1 =2
r  => 2^2 =4
chomd 740 file.txt
chown <user>:<group> <filename>  to change owner OR group OR both of a file
chown <user> <filename>
chown :<group> <filename>
chgrp <group> <filename>  to change the group of a file
chown/chmod -R <dirname> to change ownership or perm recursivly 

page: 107-114
pulic key
private key ( treated as a secret )
1. Generate a key pair ( using ssh-keygen -t <type> )
	a. this will generate a private and a publiceky with .pub extension
2. add your public key to the remote server
        a. add manually to the file ~/.ssh/authorized_keys
        b. ssh-copy-id -i <publickey> user@host
3. Authenticate using you private key 
	a. ssh -i <privatekey> user@host
	b. scp  i <privatekey> <source> user@host:<destination> => to copy file/s
	b. scp -r i <privatekey> <source> user@host:<destination> -> copy dir

If you add your private key to ~/.ssh/ , you don't have to use -i option every time to pass the privatekey
